Automated track (pure code, no LLM, no API key): ingest → indicators → rule-based screens and signals → export a structured "research pack" (per stock: latest OHLCV summary, computed indicator values, triggered signals, recent headlines collected but not interpreted). This runs on demand or on a schedule and has zero hallucination surface because no model touches it.
Interactive track (you, on your subscription): you take that research pack and paste it into Claude for the qualitative read — narrative, what-to-watch, risk framing — and when the code throws, you debug it in Claude Code. Both are interactive use, so they're covered by your plan. No API key needed anywhere.
That pushes the API key entirely off the critical path. You'd only ever add it back if you later want a truly unattended brief — say, an email every morning at 8am with nobody at the keyboard. For a human-in-the-loop research tool where you're reviewing results anyway, paste-into-Claude is the right call and costs nothing beyond your subscription.
One important correction to "whenever there's an error we look into it," though — because in market data the dangerous failures don't throw errors. A crash is easy: you see it, you fix it. The thing that quietly wrecks a research system is plausible-but-wrong data that runs clean — an unadjusted stock split doubling a price overnight, a stale candle from a holiday, a timezone bug shifting bars a day, or a symbol silently dropping out of the universe. None of those raise an exception; they just produce a confident, wrong RSI. So the automated track needs data-quality assertions that turn bad states into loud errors — checks like "no gap larger than N sessions," "close within corporate-action-adjusted bounds," "every universe symbol resolved to an instrument key." That's what makes "we look into errors" actually safe: you make the silent failures into errors you can look into.
So the roadmap reshapes slightly, and gets cheaper and simpler:

Phase 4 changes from "LLM news extraction via API" → "news collection + research-pack exporter" (all code).
Phase 5 changes from "automated agent synthesis" → a reusable analysis prompt/template you paste the pack into.
Phases 2, 3, 6 (ingest, indicators, backtest) are unchanged — they were always deterministic.
Optional later: bolt the automated API synthesis back on if you want it hands-off.

My next [ME] chunk, then, would be the research-pack exporter — the per-stock JSON/Markdown format plus the data-quality assertion layer — and a ready-made analysis prompt you can drop into Claude with the pack. None of it needs an API key, so it doesn't wait on any credentials.
